WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.360
So today I will talk about how we're going to optimize the alloconditioning regimen for patients, for older patients with AML and MDS using the triosulfam glues conditioning.

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:13.480
So this is my disclosure for this talk.

00:00:13.780 --> 00:00:20.680
Oops, that looks a little bit different, but obviously the transplant for older patients continue to increase, you know.

00:00:20.680 --> 00:00:26.580
So now we are treating patients with more comorbidities and with less biologic reserve.

00:00:26.740 --> 00:00:31.020
They have higher risk or even higher risk disease that require a curative therapy.

00:00:31.680 --> 00:00:40.600
So reduced intensity conditioning regimen definitely could help us to expand the transplant access to those patients by reducing the treatment-related mortality.

00:00:41.180 --> 00:00:45.580
But again, relapse risk is the cost that we have to pay.

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:52.920
When we think about transplant conditioning regimen, we're typically thinking about as a spectrum.

00:00:53.120 --> 00:00:56.580
So the transplant conditioning intensity score helps to...

00:00:56.740 --> 00:01:00.480
Quantify to put the given regimen along the spectrum.

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:09.480
And what it's showing here consistently, as you can see that when we increase the intensity, the treatment-related mortality also increase.

00:01:09.700 --> 00:01:12.200
And for older patients, it is amplified.

00:01:12.420 --> 00:01:14.380
So this effect is amplified with age.

00:01:14.380 --> 00:01:18.480
So for older patients, when we increase the intensity, it's not linear.

00:01:18.700 --> 00:01:20.380
It's really biological amplified.

00:01:20.580 --> 00:01:26.320
So there's really obvious needs to have a better balance between the toxicity and the antiloquemic effect.

00:01:26.680 --> 00:01:28.760
For this particular patient population.

00:01:29.660 --> 00:01:37.320
So triosulfan-based conditioning regimen could be an approach that helps us to achieve that balance.

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:43.160
So this is a prodrug alkylator with some favorable characteristics.

00:01:43.780 --> 00:01:50.160
Like, you know, predictable PK, non-enzymatic activation, consistent DNA cross-linking.

00:01:50.460 --> 00:01:54.100
So it could help to provide a reliable myeloablation.

00:01:54.660 --> 00:01:56.620
On the other hand, that it seems like...

00:01:56.620 --> 00:02:00.920
The toxicity profile could be better compared to the bosulfan-based approach.

00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:07.800
So this is one of the earliest experience with triosulfan-based conditioning at the U.S.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:18.420
So at FEDHUCH, we evaluated patients in a prospective study using triosulfan fludarabine with or without low-dose TBI.

00:02:18.420 --> 00:02:26.560
This is a high-risk patient population, including AML, MDS, CMML, and many of those patients had the features that would...

00:02:26.560 --> 00:02:28.420
Have very high risk of relapse.

00:02:29.780 --> 00:02:37.240
So what we're seeing here vary consistently across all patients on both groups that we can achieve.

00:02:37.900 --> 00:02:47.380
Very stable engraftment with no patient have graft rejection and also very stable journal chimerism on day 28 and 84.

00:02:47.380 --> 00:02:55.340
So that confirmed that the triosulfan-based conditioning could provide a very reliable conditioning platform.

00:02:55.900 --> 00:02:56.380
So when we look...

00:02:56.560 --> 00:03:04.500
At other outcomes for patients who receive additional low-dose of TBI, they have less risk of relapse.

00:03:06.060 --> 00:03:15.120
But very interestingly, that the non-relapse mortality, despite the fact with additional low-dose of TBI, it's remained really low at 9%.

00:03:15.120 --> 00:03:24.220
And this is very important, telling us that, yes, we can improve the control, the disease control when maintaining the low toxicity.

00:03:24.220 --> 00:03:25.220
So this...

00:03:26.560 --> 00:03:28.320
This is the outcomes.

00:03:28.520 --> 00:03:39.980
This is just, you know, to show you that the outcomes actually more pronounced for patient with AML and for patient with high risk of relapse, particularly for patient with unfavorable cytogenetics.

00:03:40.680 --> 00:03:46.920
So we're moving from the very encouraging single center data set to the next step.

00:03:46.920 --> 00:03:55.920
This is a phase three randomized trial that comparing the trioflurabine conditioning versus...

00:03:56.560 --> 00:04:00.660
the busulfan and fludarabine conditioning for older patient with AML/NDS.

00:04:00.660 --> 00:04:06.320
And I think that probably, you know, this is the most important randomized data set that we have in this space.

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:15.160
So in this trial, about 500 patients involved in this trial randomized one-to-one to either arms, so the age up to 70.

00:04:15.160 --> 00:04:26.180
And those patients, they required to have high comorbidity burden or other features that make them not the ideal candidate for the conventional MAC transplant approach.

00:04:26.560 --> 00:04:33.780
So looking at the EFS, we started seeing, you know, the signal favoring the triosulfan-based conditioning.

00:04:33.780 --> 00:04:40.080
So the curve separated quite early and then maintained separated over time.

00:04:40.080 --> 00:04:49.020
And very importantly, so that advantage translated to the overall survival as well, which make it much more clinically meaningful.

00:04:49.020 --> 00:04:54.680
So we look closer to see what is driving this and we can see that, you know, for the relapse rate is similar between the two.

00:04:54.680 --> 00:04:55.480
So we look closer to see what is driving this and we can see that, you know, for the relapse rate is similar between the two.

00:04:55.480 --> 00:04:56.480
So we look closer to see what is driving this and we can see that, you know, for the relapse rate is similar between the two.

00:04:56.480 --> 00:04:56.520
So we look closer to see what is driving this and we can see that, you know, for the relapse rate is similar between the two.

00:04:56.560 --> 00:05:02.240
two groups when the non-relapse mortality is significantly lower for the triosulfan-based arm.

00:05:02.620 --> 00:05:06.820
So this is telling us that, you know, this is exactly what we're looking for for the older

00:05:06.820 --> 00:05:13.440
patient population approach, like we can maintain the antiloquemic effect when reducing the toxicity

00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:20.580
of the conditioning regimen that led to the advantage of overall survival. So, you know,

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:28.920
from outside of the prospective trial, this EBMT analysis is very important because

00:05:28.920 --> 00:05:36.800
it evaluates a very challenging situation where they're comparing the outcomes of

00:05:36.800 --> 00:05:44.720
fludarabine N3014, CRAM, versus flubufor in patients with active AML, meaning primary

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:49.620
refractory or relapse disease at the time of transplant. So this is kind of the stress test

00:05:49.620 --> 00:05:50.560
of the condition.

00:05:50.580 --> 00:06:03.760
So we can see here very encouraging data as well that, you know, the patient who received the

00:06:03.760 --> 00:06:12.180
triosulfan-based, they have less relapse risk. That led to the advantage of disease-free or

00:06:12.180 --> 00:06:17.620
leukemic-free survival and overall survival. And then the non-relapse mortality, including

00:06:17.620 --> 00:06:20.560
acute and chronic GVHD, similar between the two.

00:06:20.580 --> 00:06:29.120
This is just another clinical trial to registry data, including more than 1,200 patients, again,

00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:36.000
older AML/MDS patient comparing flutrio versus flumel of SIBU. Again, I'm not going to go through

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:41.800
all the numbers here, but a couple of key points that are important for us to be aware that, you

00:06:41.800 --> 00:06:47.920
know, those patients who received the flutrio conditioning regimen have higher comorbidity

00:06:47.920 --> 00:06:54.380
abundance, that's reflecting with higher SCTCI score, age, and then, you know, performance status

00:06:54.380 --> 00:07:01.800
and disease risk seems to be very familiar across all the group. So for the AML patients, relapse

00:07:01.800 --> 00:07:08.000
risk are similar among the groups, but the non-relapse mortality obviously significantly

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:13.620
lower for the patient who received the triobase conditioning. And again, that led to the

00:07:13.620 --> 00:07:17.880
advantage of improving overall survival for patients with MDS.

00:07:17.920 --> 00:07:24.340
As you know, all the outcomes seem to be similar among the groups. So taking all together,

00:07:24.340 --> 00:07:29.380
I think that from the retrospective, from the prospective data to the registry data

00:07:29.380 --> 00:07:35.560
or slash reward data, I can see that, you know, the message is pretty consistent, that

00:07:35.560 --> 00:07:42.240
how to improve the therapeutic index in transplant, particularly for these patient population,

00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:47.900
older patient population, not only, you know, escalating the intensity, but more importantly,

00:07:47.900 --> 00:07:55.700
we have to optimize the toxicity of the conditioning. So, and of course, we taking it to the transplant

00:07:55.700 --> 00:07:59.700
to the HAPLO platform. This is the ongoing trial that we have at the Hodge. And that

